post_text:
The Boyd County Sophomores have been busy studying Greek Mythology in their English class. Their latest myth, Daedalus and Icarus, found them getting their creative juices flowing to work with a partner or my themselves, and write a poem capturing the story. The poems had to be six stanzas long with six lines in each stanza, for a total of thirty-six lines. After just a few groans and complaints about writing poetry, they got to work, and the end result was some great poems from some talented Sophomores. Click on the link below, and enjoy!

https://boydcounty.socs.net/vnews/display.v/ART/5f5badd808b10

In an ongoing attempt to ensure the safety of our students and community during the COVID 19 pandemic, Boyd County Public Schools will implement the following rules. We will be requiring masks to be worn by all spectators at indoor activities for the Fall Sports seasons. If you do not wear a mask you will be denied access to the activity. We will be offering concessions on a limited basis, offering only pre-packaged items and utilizing social distancing while at the concession area. You will be allowed to remove masks for the purpose of consuming concessions, but must wear them at all other times.

Thank you for your anticipated cooperation.

post_text:
Happy Juneteenth!!

Juneteenth is the oldest nationally celebrated commemoration of the ending of slavery in the United States. Dating back to 1865, it was on June 19th that the Union soldiers, led by Major General Gordon Granger, landed at Galveston, Texas with news that the war had ended and that the enslaved were now free.

Click the link below to learn more about this important national holdiay!

https://www.juneteenth.com/history.htm

Seniors and Senior Parents: We would like to set a date for Graduation for Saturday, July 18, 2020 at 2:00 p.m in Spencer. This graduation will take place as either A) a regular Graduation Ceremony, a Limited Attendance Graduation, or C) a pick up your Diploma Ceremony. I believe it is time to set a date so people can plan accordingly. We believe scheduling for late July will give us the best opportunity to hold a Regular Graduation Ceremony.

Michael T. Brown
Superintendent, Boyd County Schools

Teachers are preparing the last educational packest for the school year. These packets will be available for pick-up on Monday, April 27th, and will contain work through May 6th. The remainder of the school year, till May 15th, will be used to make up any missing work.

In addition, elementary teachers may not be calling you this week. Please remember, however, that they are very willing to help in any way they can so please reach out to them if your child needs any assistance with their work.

Thanks for all you are doing as parents to help continue your child's education during this unusual time. Staff is VERY appreciative of your time, support, questions and feedback.

post_text:
Sports Physicals for 2020-2021

From NSAA;
Students who have a physical on file with the school from the 2019-2020 school year are able to use this physical for the 2020-2021 school year. All incoming 9th graders (current 8th grade) will be required to provide sports physicals paperwork dated no earlier than May 1, 2020.

Current 7th-grade student/athletes who have a physical on file at school for the 2019-2020 school year can be used for activities purposes for the 2020-2021 school year. All incoming 7th-grade students (current 6th graders) will need a physical for 2020-2021.

If you have any questions, please contact Mr. Mike Shoff, Boyd County Principal/Activities Director at mshoff@boydcounty.org.

post_text:
In light of the current health issues and precautions taken to prevent the spread of the novel coronavirus, we have made the difficult decision to cancel all Career and Technical Student Organization (CTSO) 2020 State Leadership Conference/Conventions and associated large gatherings and events. While a variety of factors influenced this decision, be assured that the health and safety of our students and stakeholders is always our primary concern.

This includes:

· DECA (March 18-21)

· HOSA (March 22-24)

· Educators Rising (March 25)

· FBLA (March 30-April 1)

· FFA (April 1-3)

· SkillsUSA (April 2-4)

· FCCLA (April 5-7)

post_text:
The NSAA is aware of the fluidity of COVID-19 and the potential impact hosting statewide events could have regarding the on-going public health threat. Many of our member schools are making decisions in the best interest of their student participants, coaches and communities. The NSAA is regretfully suspending district and state speech contests until further notice.

This is an unprecedented event. The NSAA Board of Directors and staff understand the hardship this has created for our membership. The NSAA will use this time to evaluate potential alternatives and the next steps for moving forward.

Dance Camp for all Boyd County students in K-6 will be February 20, 2020 from 4:00-6:00 p.m. in the Butte gym. Our Spirit Squad will then perform at half-time of the Boys’ basketball game on February 21. The cost of the camp is $20 for 1 child, $35 for 2, and $50 for 3. Each participant will receive a t-shirt that is to be worn during the half-time performance. Please fill out the form below with your child’s information and payment, checks made out to Boyd County Public School, and return to Monica, Amy, or Mrs. Kayl by February 12. Please contact Whitney Kayl if you have any questions, 589-1333, or wkayl@boydcounty.org.

We understand that sometimes forms to not always make it home. If you are finding this to be the case, you can visit the school website to print the registration form.

Black History Month is an annual celebration of achievements by African Americans and a time for recognizing the central role of blacks in U.S. history. Also known as African American History Month, the event grew out of “Negro History Week,” the brainchild of noted historian Carter G. Woodson and other prominent African Americans.

Check back every week day of February to see which person Boyd County Schools choose to highlight for the day!

post_text:
As band parents are aware, the band is set to take a band trip on May 31st through June 2nd. If your 7-12 grader is in band you should have received a letter with an itinerary, and forms to fill out for your student. It is important to get these permission slips and forms back to Mrs. Hausmann ASAP so final payments and plans can be made for the trip to assure everything goes smoothly. If you have a child in 7-12 band and you did not receive a letter, please call the school at 402-589-1333 so we can assure you receive the paperwork.

The band will be going to Valley Fair in Minneapolis, Minnesota. We will be taking a school bus to and from Minnesota. The fundraising we have done in the last four years has covered most of the expenses for the students. They will be responsible for a few of their meals and any shopping they do while visiting the Mall of America. Permission slips MUST be returned to the school by February 7th, but the sooner we get them in the better it will be.
